folder: Greenwich Street & Christopher Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Clearing, 1-7 Christopher Street at the N.W. corner of Greenwich Avenue (right). A new apartment building is to be erected. Nos. 1 to 7 Christopher Street and 3-13 Greenwich Avenue were demolished for its site. No. 15 Greenwich Avenue, an old four-story brick house, was not carefully shored up when No. 13 was demolished, and consequently collapsed. For some years following its site will remain vacant.
October 13, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
No. 1 (1-7) Christopher Street, the completed building, beginning its first season, a year later, seen across the parking space at the S.W. corner where 1-5 Greenwich Avenue and 2-6 Christopher Street used to stand. The view at the right is northwest straight up Greenwich Avenue.
October 3, 1931.

P. L. Sperr.

folder: Christopher Street & Greenwich Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Christopher Street, south side, from No. 178 Christopher, east of West to Greenwich Streets, showing the demolition of the old houses adjoining and at the S.W. corner of Washington Street. The Barrow Street garage, the Christopher Street wing of which was at 174-168 Christopher Street, has also been demolished, and is to be replaced by a new garage for the Parmelee Transportation Company (the Yellow Cabs).

The Federal building, with its post office, customs offices, and other federal agencies, is the tall building occupying the entire block bounded by Christopher, Washington, Barrow, and Greenwich Streets.

July 25, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

folder: Christopher Street & Greenwich Street., Manhattan, NY
text:
Christopher Street, at Greenwich Street,
viewing westward, showing the "El" station built in January 31, 1867, from a design by a Swiss draftsman, who was employed in Chief Engineer Courtright's office and who contributed this Swiss chalet design. This photo was reproduced on page 90 of the published
volume "Changing New York."

June 18, 1936

Berenice Abbott, photo
Federal Art Project

title: Transportation - Elevated.

folder: Greenwich Street & Christopher Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Greenwich Street, north from Christopher Street. Shown are details of the Christopher Street station and the tracks of the old 9th Avenue Elevated Line. The photographer's vantage point
is the uptown local platform.
May 7, 1940
Views 1,2
P. L. Sperr
No.I3)
A view under the Elevated Lines showing pavement conditions. The generating plant on the right bears No. 683. At the left margin is a business building numbered 692. This location was verified by personal observation. 9-26-40
June 2, 1937
W. P. A. photo
Five Boroughs Project

folder: Greenwich Street & Christopher Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
June 27, 1973.
Pictures of the razing of 9th Ave "EP".
Taken from 663 Greenwich St.
This block of houses facing " were razed 1953 to build St. Luke's School. The old Federal style houses belonged to Trinity Church. Part of the block of houses around landmarks St. Luke's Chapel, have been restored on Hudson + Barrows Sts.) for clergy, staff and parish were 1,000,000 spent on the restorations.)
Mrs. Gilbert L. Soye.

Note:
We lived in this beautiful house 663 Greenwich St. for 18 years. The bulbs & plants from our garden were trucked to Trinity Churchyard, & many have thrived year by year. I planted the willow tree & 2 silk trees (Morus) which are now in Trinity Churchyard.
